			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What to do in groups?<a name="28948"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 19 04 2:52 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>This is a well-covered topic.  Not one you should have necessarily found -- since there's no convenient magic word to search for -- but one on which everyone has expounded repeatedly.  Allow me to sum up the advice you will get:
<br />

<br />
1.  You're doing the right things.  Please regard your understanding of what a bard's role in the group is as ratified.  Several people will describe what they do in groups, and it will be roughly similar to what you propose to do.  We're the general swiss army knife, but to the extent that we specialize in something, that something is now pulling.  
<br />

<br />
2.  The people you've been having conflicts with are bozos.  Even if they are correct as to substance -- i.e., even if the enchanter really was a good puller or even if there was a need to hurry -- their tone was inappropriate.  &quot;Sit down and play mana and stop interfering&quot; is categorically an unacceptable way to interact with another human being, and you may wish to consider not grouping with such folks again.  
<br />

<br />
3.  It will be pointed out that these conflcits are likely an inevitable consequence of relying on pickup groups.  Several people, self included, will testify that we no longer do pick up groups because they often suck.  Yes, there are good folks out there who can join pickup groups, but your chances of misery and bozodom are greatly reduced if you form a regular group of known not-dicknoses to play with.  Steppy will say &quot;Pick up groups -- JUST SAY NO.&quot;  I will say &quot;Amen!&quot;  Etc.
<br />

<br />
4.  At some point, someone will chime in to say that the warrior is right -- lull pulling is too slow.  Of course you should just charge all rooms and that way you can finish each adventure in 5 minutes or so.  Someone else will point out that it's unlikely that you and your groups are level 65 with 200+AAs and Elemental+ gear, and that perhaps -- just <i>perhaps</i> you can be trusted to make your own judgments about how many mobs you can handle at one time.
<br />

<br />
I think that about covers it.  Be at peace.  You are not laboring under a fundamental misconception of the bard's role in a group -- you've just encountered some less than optimally courteous players.  Keep kicking a$, keep taking names, and you will soon find people who appreciate the contribution you're making.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
