			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What to do in groups?<a name="29287"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 22 04 8:15 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>From my experience playing a monk, assist aggro is not shared.  This is a very important concept to understand about aggro.  Lull can reduce a two pull to a one pull.  A single lull can reduce a three pull to a two pull and a single lull can only reduce a 4 pull to a three pull.  
<br />

<br />
Since only primary aggro can call for an assist, if you understand the ranges of primary aggro assist call, which can be pretty quickly learned from mistakes when pulling, you can see how only primary aggro can get assist aggro.  
<br />

<br />
Things like hinge mobs and chain aggro are myths in my experience.  There is only primary aggro, assist aggro and chase range.  
<br />

<br />
Hinge mobs are basically an example of the misperception of aggro.  Picture in your mind a room with a mob in the center in assist call range of all four of the mobs around it (a square with a dot in the center).  Now picture circles around each of the mobs.  The circle you see around each mob is primary call for assist aggro range.  Only one of the mobs circle matters when it comes to adds, none of the others matter as long as you do not directly aggro them with your proximity or worse yet contact.
<br />

<br />
I hope this helps.
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
