			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What to do in groups?<a name="29314"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 22 04 10:19 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>What I think he means is this:
<br />

<br />
``````````````
<br />
````6````7````
<br />
``````````````
<br />
````4````5````
<br />
``````````````
<br />
```````3``````
<br />
``````````````
<br />
````1`````2```
<br />
``````````````
<br />
``````````````
<br />

<br />
If you pull #1, #2 and #3 will agro.  Some people say &quot;assist agro,&quot; some people say &quot;chain agro.&quot;  Whatever term you use, the point is:  #2 and #3 aren't in range to agro you directly.  They only come because #1 yells &quot;hey! I'm getting attacked. Come help.&quot;
<br />

<br />
Gacwin's observation is that #2 and #3 don't yell &quot;hey, come help.&quot;  If they did, #4, #5, #6 and #7 would come.  If they did, in lots of dungeons a single pull would bring the whole dungeon, as agro ripples its way down a string of mobs.
<br />

<br />
Gacwin's observation is true as far as it goes.  Just remember to know the primary agro radius of your mobs.  In some rooms with a layout like I described, casting on #1 will get you primary agro from the whole room.  
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
